ocuses on three cases: the effort to block the Americans with Disabilities Act; an attempt to reduce accident litigation by creating a no-fault auto insurance system in California; and the enactment of the Vaccine Injury Compensation Act. These cases suggest that litigious policies are deeply rooted in the American constitutional tradition. Burke shows how the diffuse, divided structure of American government, together with the anti-statist ethos of American political culture, creates incentives for political actors to use the courts to address their concerns. The first clear and comprehensive account of the national politics of litigation, his work provides a new way to understand and address the "litigiousness" of American society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aActions and defenseszUnited States. 0aJustice, Administration ofzUnited States. 0aLawyerszUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aaccident litigation.  aamerica.  aamerican culture.  aamerican government.  aamerican society.  aamericans with disabilities act.  acalifornia.  acase study.  aconstitutional tradition.  acourt centered policies.  adispute resolution.  agreed.  alawsuits.  alawyers.  alegal rights.  alegal system.  alitigation.  alitigious policies.  ano fault auto insurance system.  apolitical culture.  apolitics of litigation.  apublic life.  apublic policies.  aunited states.  avaccine injury compensation act.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052022727940uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093837340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520938373423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520938373/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California P